  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2666531756" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2666531756" />
    <a title="Alexandra" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/69833039-alexandra"><img alt="Alexandra" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1569182090p2/69833039.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2666531756?book_show_action=true">Jan 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alexandra" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alexandra" href="/user/show/69833039-alexandra">Alexandra</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780780744875" href="/book/show/9942517-bless-me-ultima">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/69833039-alexandra?shelf=diverse-books">diverse-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2666531756" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10543772033722876744">A coming-of-age story comparable to Harper Lee’s <i>To Kill a Mockingbird</i> in its exploration of complex themes through a six- or seven-year-old’s eyes. However, unlike TKaM, <i>Bless Me, Ultima</i> feels almost postmodernistically unfinished, without the arc of a completed cycle which has been executed beautifully in similar books.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


